SUMMARY:Book Talk with Dr. Sophia Rodriguez: "Undocumented in the U.S. Sout
 h"
DESCRIPTION:Organized by: ['Educational Studies'\, 'ENLACE'\, 'Peace and Co
 nflict Studies'\, 'Sociology and Anthropology'\, 'Swatties for Immigrant R
 ights'\, 'Teaching and Learning Commons']\\nCategory: Lecture/Panel Discus
 sion\\nDr. Sophia Rodriguez Undocumented in the U.S. South: How Youth Navi
 gate Racialization in Policy and School Contexts Undocumented in the U.S. 
 South: How Youth Navigate Racialization in Policy and School Contexts is a
  rare look into the everyday realities of undocumented youth in K-12 publi
 c schools. In an anti-immigrant policy context\, youth and their families 
 navigate historical and current legacies and realities of segregation\, ra
 cial discrimination\, and inequality. With a deep three-year ethnographic 
 study\, hundreds of hours of observational research\, interviews\, and pol
 icy analysis\, Sophia Rodriguez traces the lives of undocumented youth acr
 oss multiple public school settings. Her research underscores how these yo
 uth are racialized through state policies\, school and organizational prac
 tices\, and everyday interactions with educators and peers. As the first s
 tudy of its kind to combine this unique framework for analysis\, Undocumen
 ted in the U.S. South sheds light on the challenges youth face in their ev
 eryday struggle to belong. Rodriguez invites us to consider youth experien
 ces as central knowledge for improving educators’ awareness and school p
 ractice\, while promoting policies that are humanizing and rooted in youth
  experience. Dr. Sophia Rodriguez is an Associate Professor of Educational
  Policy and Leadership and Sociology of Education at New York University's
  Steinhardt School of Culture\, Education\, and Human Development. Dr. Rod
 riguez's Ph.D. is in Cultural and Educational Policy Studies and Sociology
 . She is broadly interested in education policy and reform\, racial and et
 hnic identity formation in schools\, immigrant youth belonging to school a
 nd society. She has teaching experience at the secondary (English Educatio
 n and ESL for grades 7-12) and post-secondary level in New York City and C
 hicago. \\nDetails: https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%
 3Devent%26eventid%3D1374056031
LOCATION:Hormel/Nguyen Intercultural Center at Sproul Hall Room 201 Dome Ro
 om
URL:https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%
 3D1374056031
CATEGORIES:Lecture/Panel Discussion
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:d146282310e5f99b@swarthmore-dash-calendar
DTSTAMP:20260322T113036Z
DTSTART:20260323T203000Z
DTEND:20260323T213000Z
SUMMARY:The Model Migrant and the Colonial Mindset: Narratives of German Se
 ttlement in the Midwest and Africa
DESCRIPTION:Organized by: ['German'\, 'Modern Languages and Literatures']\\
 nCategory: Lecture/Panel Discussion\\nThe nineteenth century was character
 ized by German migration to different parts of the world\, including the U
 nited States and some parts of Africa. At the same time\, Germany\, drawin
 g from American Westward expansion\, became a colonial power and subsequen
 tly\, the third most powerful colonizing nation after Britain and France. 
 This presentation examines the role of popular media in creating and susta
 ining an image of Germans both as model migrants and as unique colonizers.
  The presentation critiques these two narratives through the coverage of h
 istorical events in the United States and in Africa at the Turn of the Cen
 tury. It also pays attention to the connection between German colonial exp
 loits in Africa and the Third Reich. Bio: Dr. Peter Ogunniran is an Assist
 ant Professor in the Department of German and Russian at Williams College.
  He holds a PhD in German and Comparative Literature\, and a graduate cert
 ificate in Higher Education Administration from Washington University in S
 aint Louis. He completed his master’s in Modern Languages at the Univers
 ity of Mississippi and received his bachelor’s degree in European Studie
 s (German) from the University of Ibadan\, Ibadan Nigeria. At Williams Col
 lege\, he teaches German language classes at different levels as well as s
 eminars including (In)Justice and Morals in German Literature\, The Other 
 Germans: Exploring Diversity in Contemporary German Literature\, Literatur
 e as Resistance\, Heimat: Identity\, Belonging and Home in German Literatu
 re\, as well as Europe and the Black Diaspora. His research areas include 
 German colonial literature and history\, nationalism\, public media and vi
 sual culture\, Afro-German studies and family narratives. His current rese
 arch investigates the mediation of nationalism and the colonial Other in G
 erman colonies in the late 19th and early 20th centuries\; the roles of pu
 blic media such as family magazine\, literature for children and adults\; 
 and the role of public spaces in mediating nationalism and national identi
 ty.\\nDetails: https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Deven
 t%26eventid%3D1360880964
LOCATION:Kohlberg Room 115-Classroom
URL:https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%
 3D1360880964
CATEGORIES:Lecture/Panel Discussion
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
