SUMMARY:CS is Dead. Long Live CS.
DESCRIPTION:Organized by: ['Computer Science']\\nCategory: Academic Event\\
 n"Over the last 10-15 years\, almost everybody who sits on a stage like th
 is would tell you that it is vital that your children learn computer scien
 ce\; everybody should learn how to program. And it's almost exactly the op
 posite.“ Jensen Huang\, CEO NVIDIA\, 2024 “Big Tech Told Kids to Code.
  The Jobs Didn’t Follow.” New York Times The Daily. September 2025. 
 “We’re considering scaling back our coding curriculum to make room for
  AI literacy instead. After all\, these students will likely be prompting 
 AI to write code rather than writing it themselves.” Education Week\, Se
 ptember 2025. We’ve heard this story before. The argument is always the 
 same: the tools have gotten so good that understanding what's underneath n
 o longer matters. And the argument is always wrong. In this talk\, I'll ma
 ke the case that computer science isn't just still relevant in the age of 
 AI\; it's foundational knowledge that every student will need. I'll discus
 s how the Computer Science Teachers Association developed and continues to
  evolve the CSTA K-12 standards\, how we are navigating the pressure to tr
 eat "AI literacy" as a standalone discipline\, and why stripping CS out of
  that conversation puts students at risk of becoming passive consumers rat
 her than informed creators. I'll also share my own path from Swarthmore CS
  graduate to leading a national education nonprofit as one example of how 
 a CS background opens doors far beyond the tech industry. Finally\, partic
 ipants will work through an activity designed to surface a deceptively har
 d question: What are the core concepts and competencies that a student ent
 ering kindergarten today will need to thrive when they enter the workforce
  in 2040? The answers should shape how we teach computer science right now
 . This talk is for anyone who cares about the future of CS education. Whet
 her you’re a CS major heading to industry\, an educator heading into you
 r first classroom\, or a future policy leader who wants to improve equitab
 le education for all this talk is for you. Speaker BioJake Baskin '10 is E
 xecutive Director of the Computer Science Teachers Association (CSTA)\, th
 e largest membership organization for CS educators in the world. Under his
  leadership\, CSTA has grown from insolvency to a thriving $10M+ organizat
 ion with 10\,000+ members and chapters across three continents. Jake has r
 epresented CS educators at the White House\, the National Governors Associ
 ation\, and international conferences. Previously\, he helped build Code.o
 rg into a national movement for K-12 computer science education. Jake got 
 his start teaching CS and coaching basketball at Lindblom Math and Science
  Academy\, a Chicago Public School. His path began with a computer science
  degree (and a lot of poetry classes) from Swarthmore. He's excited to be 
 back on campus.\\nDetails: https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed
 =view%3Devent%26eventid%3D1373113775
LOCATION:Science Center Room 101- Chang Hou Hall Tiered Classroom
URL:https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%
 3D1373113775
CATEGORIES:Academic Event
END:VEVENT
