SUMMARY:P&A Colloquium: Lamiya Mowla\, Wellesley
DESCRIPTION:Organized by: ['Physics and Astronomy']\\nCategory: Lecture/Pan
 el Discussion\\nSpring 2026  Physics and Astronomy Colloquium Friday\, Ap
 ril 3\, 2026\, 12:45 pm\, Cunniff Lecture Hall (SCI 199) Lamiya MowlaAssis
 tant Professor Physics and AstronomyWellesley College Observing the Birth
  and Growth of Galaxies since the Big Bang How did galaxies like our Milky
  Way form? To answer this question\, astronomers look back to the early ye
 ars of the Universe\, when the first galaxies were just beginning to take 
 shape. Using the James Webb Space Telescope (JWST)\, we can now study gala
 xies from a time when the Universe was only about 5 percent of its current
  age. In this talk\, I will share observations of distant galaxies nicknam
 ed the “Firefly Sparkle\,” whose light has traveled more than 13 billi
 on years to reach us. This young galaxy is forming from compact\, intense 
 star clusters and offers a glimpse into the early stages of growth that ev
 entually led to galaxies like our own Milky Way. I will also present new r
 esults from extending this work to more galaxies\, allowing us to trace ho
 w star clusters and galaxies grew together across cosmic history. Finally\
 , I will highlight projects being built with Wellesley students that broad
 en access to astronomy research and its history. These include J-HIVE\, a 
 public data and visualization platform for galaxies observed with JWST\, a
 nd Mirror\, an initiative that preserves the erased histories of women ast
 ronomers through a digital archive and a permanent exhibit at Whitin Obser
 vatory in celebration of its 125 years. BIO: Prof. Mowla is an Assistant P
 rofessor of Astronomy at Wellesley College. She earned her Ph.D. from Yale
  University in 2020 under the mentorship of Prof. Pieter van Dokkum. Befor
 e joining Wellesley\, she was a Dunlap Postdoctoral Fellow at the Dunlap I
 nstitute for Astronomy and Astrophysics\, University of Toronto. She is or
 iginally from Dhaka\, Bangladesh\, and is an inaugural Associate Member of
  the Center for Astronomy\, Space Science\, and Astrophysics at Independen
 t University\, Bangladesh—the first astronomy research center in the cou
 ntry. The colloquium will begin promptly at 12:45 p.m. in Science Center 1
 99. A pizza lunch will be available at 12:25 p.m. \\nDetails: https://swat
 central.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%3D1358005007
LOCATION:Science Center Room 199-Cunniff Hall Tiered Classroom\, Science Ce
 nter Room 199-Cunniff Hall Lobby
URL:https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%
 3D1358005007
CATEGORIES:Lecture/Panel Discussion
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
