SUMMARY:Writing Cross Cultures\, Working Between Languages: The Translation
 al Prism of Taiwan
DESCRIPTION:Organized by: ['Chinese'\, 'Asian Studies'\, 'Comparative Liter
 ature'\, 'Global Studies Program'\, 'Japanese'\, 'Modern Languages and Lit
 eratures'\, 'Russian']\\nCategory: Lecture/Panel Discussion\\nThis talk ex
 plores the intricate histories and human connections embedded in contempor
 ary Taiwanese literature—works that strive to reclaim forbidden memories
  and navigate the identity of a multilingual\,immigrant society. Using tra
 nslation as a "prism\," we will examine the diverse facets of Taiwanese cu
 lture and the power of literary translation to capture the subtle nuances 
 of shifting linguistic practices. Featuring Lin King Lin King is an acclai
 med writer and translator from Taiwan. A 2018 winner of the PEN/Robert J. 
 Dau Short Story Prize\, she reached a career milestone in 2024 as a winner
  of the National Book Award for Translated Literature. Joining us to discu
 ss the challenges and promises of the craft\, she will focus on three of h
 er major translated works: Taiwan Travelogue: A Novel\, The Boy from Clear
 water\, and A Perfect Day to Put Your Head into the Oven.Sponsored by Mode
 rn Languages and Literatures (Chinese\, Japanese and Russian Sections)\, A
 sian Studies\, Comparative Literature and Global Studies Contact: Claire L
 i\; cli3@swarthmore.edu\\nDetails: https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?tru
 mbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%3D1376027666
LOCATION:Kohlberg Hall Scheuer Room - Multi-Purpose Room
URL:https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%
 3D1376027666
CATEGORIES:Lecture/Panel Discussion
END:VEVENT
